article.headline: Hamilton's 25 lead Pistons
article.linkText: Pistons beat Wizards, win eighth of last nine
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Larry Brown applauded Detroit's defensive performance, while Chauncey Billups was just satisfied to get the victory. Richard Hamilton scored 25 points and Billups added 22 to lead the Pistons to their eighth win in nine games against Washington, an 80-69 victory over the Wizards on Saturday night. Detroit held Washington to a season-low point total, including just nine points in the third quarter when the Wizards shot 3-for-21. "We defended pretty good," Brown said. "They only got 23 points in the second half." Billups had a different opinion. "It wasn't a win that was very impressive, but it was a good win," Billups said. "If we can win ugly 70 times, I'll take 70 wins." Detroit's victory overshadowed a solid game by Brendan Haywood, who led the Wizards with a career-high 23 points and season-high 11 rebounds. "I definitely felt we had to establish ourselves in the post with Ben Wallace in there," Haywood said. "We wanted to make sure that he had something to think about. We did not want him to roam around and block everyone's shot." Wallace blocked just one shot, but he altered several drives to the basket. "He didn't play a lot in the second half," Brown said. "I know how much we need him late. "I gave him a blow in the third quarter. even though we were going good. Given the blow, he came back and he had a lot of energy." Moments after Jarvis Hayes tied the game at 65 with a dunk with 6:57 remaining, Washington coach Eddie Jordan drew a technical for charging onto the court as Hamilton was making a layup. "I thought it was a travel," said Jordan, who was trying to call timeout after Billups collided with Blake in the frontcourt. "That's the heartbreak part about it. It was there in my mind, but they didn't call it and that's a crucial play for us." Hamilton made the free throw for a 68-65 lead with 6:37 left and the Pistons never trailed again. Billups' 3-pointer from the corner gave the Pistons a 76-69 lead with 1:32 left. Mehmet Okur scored 10 points for the Pistons, who got 11 rebounds from Ben Wallace. Billups scored five points early in the third quarter to give the Pistons a 48-46 lead while the Wizards missed their first 10 shots of the period. The Pistons went on an 11-0 run to take a 52-46 lead before Haywood scored Washington's first points of the third at the 5:10 mark. The Wizards shot 3-for-21 in the quarter. Haywood made seven of his first nine shots and had five rebounds in the game's first 15 minutes. His dunk for a three-point play gave Washington a 33-25 lead with 9:35 remaining in the second quarter. The Wizards ended the first quarter with an 11-4 run. Hughes scored nine of 11 points for Washington as the Wizards took a 46-39 lead late in the second quarter. Hamilton, who scored a career-high 44 points Friday night against Cleveland, scored eight of the Pistons' first 18 points.

Game notes
The Pistons put Lindsay Hunter on the injured list with a strained left MCL before the game and activated Hubert Davis. ... The Wizards activated Mitchell Butler for the spot vacated by leading scorer Gilbert Arenas, who has missed the last three games with an abdominal strain. ... Etan Thomas missed the game with the flu.
